MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property SelectedEndTime As DateTime
public: property DateTime SelectedEndTime { DateTime get(); };

Docs.summary: Returns a DateTime value that represents the end time of a selection in the object. Read-only.

remarks.para: The intent of the and the SelectedEndTime properties is to replicate, programmatically, the way that users create an appointment in the Microsoft Outlook user interface. Typically, a user selects a time range in the calendar view and then creates a new appointment by double clicking the selection or by clicking New Appointment in the Home tab of the Microsoft Office Fluent ribbon. With these two properties of the CalendarView object, you can obtain the start time and the end time of any selection in that view programmatically. You can then programmatically create the object, setting the and properties of the AppointmentItem object to the SelectedStartTime and SelectedEndTime properties respectively to reflect any user selection in the calendar view.
If the selection in the calendar view is a time range and is not an item, SelectedEndTime returns a DateTime value equal to the end time of the selection.

If one or more items are selected in the calendar view, SelectedEndTime returns a DateTime value equal to the end time of the first item in the selection of the explorer that displays the calendar view. That selection is specified by the property of the object.

To use this property on a CalendarView object, obtain the CalendarView object from the property of the active Explorer object (which can be returned by the method). There is a known issue with using this property on an CalendarView object obtained otherwise - using the property of the current object (returned by the property of the object represented by Application.ActiveExplorer).

MemberSignature.Value: public: property System::String ^ XML { System::String ^ get(); void set(System::String ^ value); };

Docs.summary: Returns or sets a String (string in C#) value that specifies the XML definition of the view. Read/write.

remarks.para: The XML definition describes the view type by using a series of tags and keywords corresponding to various properties of the view itself. When the view is created, the XML definition is parsed to render the settings for the new view.
To determine how the XML should be structured when creating views, you can create a view by using the Outlook user interface and then you can retrieve the XML property for that view.
